WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.060
There is a small canal, it is a remnant of

2
00:00:05.060 --> 00:00:07.140
this hyaloid vessel

3
00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:12.020
and a fine canal currently remains in the eye

4
00:00:12.020 --> 00:00:17.380
which leads us directly to a primary axis

5
00:00:17.380 --> 00:00:17.980
important

6
00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:21.360
which is called Cloquet's canal.

7
00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:27.360
And you see it here, you see, it's a remnant in this

8
00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:27.800
humor

9
00:00:28.791 --> 00:00:30.771
you have different humors

10
00:00:30.771 --> 00:00:32.951
this is the humor

11
00:00:32.951 --> 00:00:35.131
aqueous and then the vitreous humor

12
00:00:35.131 --> 00:00:36.811
and the vitreous humor

13
00:00:36.811 --> 00:00:37.951
you really have to imagine

14
00:00:37.951 --> 00:00:39.311
that it's like a balloon

15
00:00:41.351 --> 00:00:43.091
of gelatinous water

16
00:00:43.731 --> 00:00:44.891
that is in the eye

17
00:00:44.891 --> 00:00:46.191
that floats

18
00:00:46.191 --> 00:00:47.311
of water

19
00:00:47.311 --> 00:00:49.311
with at its center

20
00:00:49.951 --> 00:00:51.231
a fine canal

21
00:00:52.211 --> 00:00:54.891
which comes directly onto the lens here

22
00:00:56.142 --> 00:01:01.162
You see, here, which is a direct axis with the

23
00:01:01.162 --> 00:01:05.662
optic nerve, or the hyaloid canal.

24
00:01:06.542 --> 00:01:11.982
So the lens, it comes from your skin, surface ectoderm.

25
00:01:14.502 --> 00:01:20.062
Invagination, fifth week, lens vesicle is surrounded by vascularized mesenchyme.

26
00:01:21.422 --> 00:01:24.142
Then, I have this connection.

27
00:01:24.213 --> 00:01:26.653
Juxtacrine, the placode

28
00:01:26.653 --> 00:01:28.473
invaginates and will become

29
00:01:28.473 --> 00:01:30.253
the lens. It's the same movement

30
00:01:30.253 --> 00:01:32.093
as a neural tube. Poof, touc!

31
00:01:32.093 --> 00:01:34.653
Inside, there remains a space,

32
00:01:34.653 --> 00:01:35.953
which we call the crystalline lens.

33
00:01:36.533 --> 00:01:38.473
There is a whole evolution of this crystalline lens

34
00:01:38.473 --> 00:01:39.293
which will form

35
00:01:40.193 --> 00:01:42.213
primitive lines, etc.

36
00:01:42.513 --> 00:01:43.513
I will skip this part.

37
00:01:43.853 --> 00:01:45.793
It's important to understand how it forms

38
00:01:45.793 --> 00:01:48.273
like a neural tube, and it becomes

39
00:01:48.273 --> 00:01:49.633
here, on its own.

40
00:01:49.873 --> 00:01:51.553
It is truly the lens

41
00:01:51.553 --> 00:01:52.213
of the eye.

42
00:01:53.324 --> 00:01:58.344
You see here the colobomic fissure; there is a line here

43
00:01:58.344 --> 00:02:03.364
below, you see, and that's what will later form, with the arteries, the canal of

44
00:02:03.364 --> 00:02:03.704
Cloquet.

45
00:02:04.184 --> 00:02:10.164
It will close with the hyaloid artery and vein, which is central; this

46
00:02:10.164 --> 00:02:15.564
important artery, this is a colobomic fissure in the eye

47
00:02:15.564 --> 00:02:17.764
that is not closed.

48
00:02:21.375 --> 00:02:23.495
What is this?

49
00:02:24.095 --> 00:02:26.475
It is the primary lens vesicle

50
00:02:26.475 --> 00:02:29.275
which becomes a secondary lens vesicle

51
00:02:29.275 --> 00:02:32.655
with the lens placode; this is the crystalline lens,

52
00:02:34.595 --> 00:02:36.995
juxtacrine, integration, you see.

53
00:02:46.815 --> 00:02:48.355
With the layer.

54
00:02:48.426 --> 00:02:53.906
Here, which will form what we call, externally,

55
00:02:54.246 --> 00:02:57.706
it is the sclera, the first coat.

56
00:02:58.226 --> 00:03:04.186
The second coat is here, all

57
00:03:04.186 --> 00:03:07.346
of this, in fact, is the choroid

58
00:03:07.346 --> 00:03:10.866
which will form the attachment with the crystalline lens.

59
00:03:11.686 --> 00:03:16.426
Anterior chamber, posterior chamber in the part.

60
00:03:16.497 --> 00:03:19.897
anterior. So I can divide the eye into parts.

61
00:03:20.757 --> 00:03:24.717
forward and backward, and in the anterior part, I divide it

62
00:03:24.717 --> 00:03:28.777
into anterior chambers and posterior chambers. Then, we have

63
00:03:28.777 --> 00:03:32.517
what is called the

64
00:03:32.517 --> 00:03:35.977
conjunctiva, the cornea,

65
00:03:37.497 --> 00:03:40.497
which is in continuity, conjunctiva,

66
00:03:42.497 --> 00:03:44.497
cornea, and the cornea is in continuity.

67
00:03:44.568 --> 00:03:48.068
Continuity with the sclera.

68
00:03:48.408 --> 00:03:54.468
And what do we call the part here,

69
00:03:54.648 --> 00:03:58.908
the second, we called it the choroid.

70
00:03:59.128 --> 00:04:01.228
We call it the uvea.

71
00:04:02.008 --> 00:04:06.268
And the uvea, it comes from the Latin uva, which means grape.

72
00:04:07.328 --> 00:04:11.488
This small membrane, like this, is a membrane very rich in vessels.

73
00:04:11.488 --> 00:04:12.568
It divides into three.

74
00:04:12.639 --> 00:04:17.799
parts, or into two or three major parts, which we call the choroid

75
00:04:17.799 --> 00:04:21.139
here, and anteriorly

76
00:04:21.139 --> 00:04:25.659
the cornea, and the cornea is transparent.

77
00:04:26.499 --> 00:04:32.159
But here posteriorly, there will be the iris, which

78
00:04:32.159 --> 00:04:35.919
is a continuity of the choroid, and

79
00:04:35.919 --> 00:04:40.479
we will have here connections, a ligament.

80
00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:43.250
which we call the suspensory ligament of the iris,

81
00:04:44.050 --> 00:04:44.970
which maintains the iris,

82
00:04:45.390 --> 00:04:49.230
with small muscles called the ciliary muscles,

83
00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:51.110
which will...

84
00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:54.410
We will see that in a bit more detail later.

85
00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:56.410
So the retina, in fact,

86
00:04:57.490 --> 00:04:59.670
is the innermost layer of the eye.

87
00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:02.190
Do you remember this first vesicle,

88
00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:03.650
this small sphere that emerges,

89
00:05:03.770 --> 00:05:08.270
which we call the primary optic vesicle.

90
00:05:08.781 --> 00:05:13.841
which will make a movement like this, you see, like a

91
00:05:13.841 --> 00:05:14.841
calyx, a vessel.

92
00:05:15.321 --> 00:05:20.421
It is made of two layers, an inner layer and an outer layer.

93
00:05:20.701 --> 00:05:24.221
And this is where one understands what is called a retinal detachment.

